pd.merge() joins two DataFrames together based on a common column, like a SQL JOIN.

Basic example:
```python
df1 = pd.DataFrame({
    "country": ["Spain", "France", "Italy"],
    "population": [47, 67, 59]
})

df2 = pd.DataFrame({
    "country": ["Spain", "France", "Germany"],
    "capital": ["Madrid", "Paris", "Berlin"]
})

result = pd.merge(df1, df2, on="country")
```

Result — only matching rows kept:
```bash
country  population capital
    Spain          47  Madrid
   France          67   Paris
```

The how parameter controls which rows survive:
"inner" (default) — only rows that match in both DataFrames.
"left" — all rows from df1, fill NaN where df2 has no match.
"right" — all rows from df2, fill NaN where df1 has no match.
"outer" — all rows from both, NaN wherever there's no match.
```python

pd.merge(df1, df2, on="country", how="outer")

```
```bash

   country  population capital
     Spain        47.0  Madrid
    France        67.0   Paris
     Italy        59.0     NaN
   Germany         NaN  Berlin

```

When column names differ between the two DataFrames:
```python
pd.merge(df1, df2, left_on="country_name", right_on="nation")
```
Merging on multiple columns:
```python
pd.merge(df1, df2, on=["country", "year"])
```
It keeps all columns from both DataFrames. 
The key column appears once (not duplicated).
```python
df1: ["country", "population"]
df2: ["country", "capital"]

pd.merge(df1, df2, on="country")
# columns: ["country", "population", "capital"]
```

When both DataFrames have a non-key column with the same name, pandas adds 
suffixes to distinguish them:
```python
df1 = pd.DataFrame({"country": ["Spain"], "value": [10]})
df2 = pd.DataFrame({"country": ["Spain"], "value": [99]})

pd.merge(df1, df2, on="country")
  country  value_x  value_y
    Spain       10       99
```
_x comes from the left DataFrame, _y from the right. You can customize them:
```python
pd.merge(df1, df2, on="country", suffixes=("_pop", "_gdp"))
# columns: ["country", "value_pop", "value_gdp"]
``

