# NaN.

to remove rows wiht Nan value dropna() helsp us.

dropna also works on DataFrame.

On a DataFrame, the how parameter controls the behavior:
```python
df.dropna()              # drops row if ANY column has NaN (default)
df.dropna(how="all")     # drops row only if ALL columns are NaN
```

You can also limit it to specific columns:

```python
df.dropna(subset=["income", "population"])  # only checks these columns
```
And axis lets you drop columns instead of rows:
```python

df.dropna(axis=1)        # drops COLUMNS that have any NaN
```

So the default (how="any", axis=0) is the strictest — one NaN anywhere in the row and it's gone.

